&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; On a number of occasions I have written a TestCase where setUp()
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; creates an object that uses the file system and tearDown() clears
&gt;&gt; the
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; entire tree used by that object. I have never successfully had
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; tearDown() finish before setUp() started for the next test, owing
to
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; the fact (I suppose) that the JVM does not block on the system
call.
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; I ended up doing what you suggest: I use a different root
directory
&gt;&gt; for
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; each test, usually calling it something like
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;     root-&lt;testClassName&gt;-&lt;testName&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; I then add a shutdown hook to clean them all up.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;I have a similar test situation where I am testing agasinst a smart
&gt;&gt; card
&gt;&gt; &gt;and
&gt;&gt; &gt;my solution
&gt;&gt; &gt;was to synchronize on my test fixture in setUp(), tearDown() and
each
&gt;&gt; test
&gt;&gt; &gt;case. This ensured that my tests ran synchronously and that the
smart
&gt;&gt; card
&gt;&gt; &gt;was properly cleaned up before the next test started.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Has anyone used Prevayler? If so, have you come up with any
&gt;&gt; strategies
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; for unit testing against the Prevayler without changing its
source?
&gt;&gt; I
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; have been considering refactoring Prevayler to talk to byte
streams
&gt;&gt; and
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; having one wrapper around it that uses the file system for
&gt;&gt; production
&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; and another wrapper that keeps everything in memory for test.
